[2 bladen] [blad 1, recto] Speelman, 16-10-73. Peasants tying Faggots. Thin oak. 331/2 x 261/2 cm, 133/10" x 101/2". Man on left in white violet short jacket over white shirt, trousers reddish grey brown not in good condition (stippled by restorer). Man on right greenish grey, over white shirt. In the fleshparts of both some red with white highlights. Brown eyes. The man on the ladder: black grey, trousers, greenish blue jacket, grey & hair cap; [blad 1, verso] The tool greenish blue like the dress - very heavy no detail. Trunk of the tree on which this man is working simply grey-very little differentiated. The brandles of faggots grey with white highlights. Some parallel strokes of underdrawing in white shirt of man on right. Soil, brown, and behind this green (meadow) very summary. Left leg of man with a kind of pentimenti; [blad 2, recto] The forest- green shrubs on left and centre; the tree trunks and branches dark brown grey with reddish and white highlights. Black cap on the ground bottom left (next to purse) black with grey spots, but without the 'pointllist' quality of P.B.I-too coarse. The whistle on the right does not appear in teh X-ray photograph. Grey trousers of right man painted broadly in P.B.I manner; [blad 2, verso] On back old number in [schema]. Provenance: Prince Wallenstein? in Germany or rather Oethinger-Wallenstein? There is a lithographed (1826?) and MS Catal. (1827) in Munich, Photostats in Nat. Gall. Better than Barber Institute. Oethinger-Wallenstein Coll. see also G. Grupp, in Jahrbuch des histor. Vereins f√ºr Nordlingen & Umgebung, VI, 1907, pp. 73ff. (All this about Oethinger-Wallenstein Coll. according to N.G. Catal. German School. Sale of Oethinger-Wallenstein Coll. at Kensington Pal. 1848, bt by Prince Consort.
